%text Remember \item{Only one line can pass through two points} \item{Whilst infinite lines can pass through a point, only one of those lines can have a given slope} In the table below, $A$ and $B$ are two points and $m$ is the slope of the line Depending on what you know, the table also shows \underline\text{how to find the equation} of the line
% \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{NNNN}
\hline A & B & m & \text{Equation} \\ \hline \checkmark & \checkmark & \text{X} & \frac{y-y_A}{x- x_A} = \frac{y_B - y_A}{x_B - x_A} \\ \hline \checkmark & \text{X} & \checkmark & \frac{y-y_A}{x-x_A} = m \\ \hline \text{X} & \checkmark & \checkmark & \frac{y - y_B}{x-x_B} = m \\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text \textbf{\small{If given the intercepts} } If you are told that the line cuts the $x$-axis at $A = \left(a,0 \right)$ and the $y$-axis at $B = \left(0,b \right)$, then the equation of the line is % \begin{align}
\frac{y - 0}{x-a} &= \frac{b-0}{0-a} \implies -ay = bx - ba \\ \therefore bx + ay &= ba \implies \underbrace{\frac{x}{a} + \frac{y}{b} = 1}_{\text{Divide throught by $a\cdot b$}}\\ \end{align} %text %
